 Africa|Area code]]\n| area_code                       = 021\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Stellenbosch''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|t|\u025b|l|\u0259|n|b|\u0252|\u0283}};<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/stellenbosch|title=Definition of STELLENBOSCH|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-16}}</ref> {{IPA-af|\u02c8st\u00e6l\u0259n\u02ccb\u0254s|lang}})<ref name=\"Baldwin1852\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=vtBiaIcwA5QC&pg=PT153&as_brr=1&ei=BFiUR83LFoeC7gKLnIyZBw A Universal Pronouncing Gazetteer.] Thomas Baldwin, 1852. Philadelphia: Lippincott, Grambo & Co.</ref><ref name=\"Donaldson1993\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ftzioRvJzTUC&pg=PA39&ei=v1eUR6GRAZD26wLBmsGvBw&sig=OqXPC4xAKmT6DvJZFBV48aejJAs A Grammar of Afrikaans.] Bruce C. Donaldson. 1993. Berlin: Walter de Gruyter. {{ISBN|3-11-013426-8}}</ref> is a town in the [[Western Cape]] province of [[South Africa]], situated about {{convert|50|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} east of [[Cape Town]], along the banks of the [[Eerste River]] at the foot of the [[Stellenbosch Mountain]]. It is the second oldest [[Europe]]an settlement in the province, after [[Cape Town]]. The town became known as the City of Oaks or ''Eikestad'' in [[Afrikaans]] and [[Dutch language|Dutch]] due to the large number of [[oak]] trees that were planted by its founder, [[Simon van der Stel]], to grace the streets and homesteads.<ref name=\"Rees\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=02EIAAAAQAAJ&pg=PT139&as_brr=1&ei=2omHR4CyMZ-QiQGn24TEBQ#v=onepage&q=stellenbosch&f=false ''The Cyclop\u00e6dia; or, Univeal Dictionary of Arts, Sciences, and Literature.''] Abraham Rees, 1819. London: Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme & Brown</ref>\n\nStellenbosch has its own municipality (incorporating the neighbouring towns of [[Pniel, Western Cape|Pniel]] and [[Franschhoek]]), adjoining the [[metropolitan area]] of the [[City of Cape Town]]. The town is home to [[University of Stellenbosch|Stellenbosch University]]. [[Technopark Stellenbosch|Technopark]] is a modern science park situated on the southern side of the town near the [[Stellenbosch Golf Course]].\n\n== Prehistory ==\n[[File:Biface Stellenbosch MHNT PRE 2009.0.195.1 Global fond.jpg|thumb|Left|[[Paleolithic]] [[biface]] from Stellenbosch]]\nIn 1899 [[Louis P\u00e9ringuey]] discovered [[Paleolithic]] [[stone tool]]s of the [[Acheulean]] [[archaeological culture|type]] at a site named Bosman's Crossing near the Adam Tas Bridge at the western entrance to Stellenbosch.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Seddon|first=J. D.|journal=The South African Archaeological Bulletin|date=October 1966|volume=21|issue=83|pages=133\u2013137|publisher=South African Archaeological Society|title=The Early Stone Age at Bosman's Crossing, Stellenbosch|jstor=3888433}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Butzer|editor1-first=Karl W.|editor2-last=Isaac|editor2-first=Glynn L.|last=Deacon|first=H. J.|chapter=Demography, Subsistence, and Culture During the Acheulian in Southern Africa|title=After the Australopithecines: Stratigraphy, Ecology, and Culture Change in the Middle Pleistocene|date=1975|isbn=9783110878837|pages=543\u2013570|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-wQwW3WO5CkC&dq}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Bletterman House (corner view).JPG|thumb|right|Typical [[Cape Dutch architecture|Cape Dutch]] style house in Stellenbosch]]\nThe town was founded in 1679 by the Governor of the [[Cape Colony]], [[Simon van der Stel]], who named it after himself<ref name=Fairbridge-105>{{cite book|last=Fairbridge|first=Dorothea|title=Historic houses of South Africa|year=1922|publisher=H. Milford, Oxford university press|location=London|page=109|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924014905834#page/n195/mode/2up/search/stellenbosch|accessdate=31 January 2011|chapter=XII \u2013 Stellenbosch}}</ref> \u2013 Stellenbosch means \"(van der) Stel's Bush\". It is situated on the banks of the Eerste River (\"First River\"), so named as it was the first new river he reached and followed when he went on an expedition over the Cape Flats to explore the territory towards what is now known as Stellenbosch. The town grew so quickly that it became an independent local authority in 1682 and the seat of a [[magistrate]] with jurisdiction over {{convert|25000|km2|sqmi|sp=us}} in 1685.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://showme.co.za/stellenbosch/tourism/history-of-stellenbosch/|title=History of Stellenbosch|website=ShowMe\u2122 \u2013 Stellenbosch|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-06}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Dutch people|Dutch]] were skilled in hydraulic engineering and they devised a system of furrows to direct water from the Eerste River in the vicinity of Thibault Street through the town along van Riebeeck Street to Mill Street where a [[Watermill|mill]] was erected.<ref name=\"Martin\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pv0zAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA496 ''Statistics of the Colonies of the British Empire in the West Indies, South America, North America, Asia, Austral-Asia, Africa and Europe: From the Official Records of the Colonial Office.''] [[Robert Montgomery Martin]], 1839. London: W.H. Allen and Co. (p. 496)</ref><ref name=\"Bird1822\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=aRoPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA174 State of the Cape of Good Hope, in 1822.] [[William Wilberforce Bird (MP)|William Wilberforce Bird]]. 1823. London: J. Murray.</ref> Early visitors commented on the oak trees and gardens.<ref name=\"Rees\"/><ref name=\"Backhouse\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=u0YFAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA498 ''The Life and Labours of George Washington Walker: of Hobart Town, Tasmania.''] James Backhouse and Charles Tylor, 1862. Tasmania: Thomas Brady (pp. 498\u2013499)</ref>\n\nDuring 1690 some [[Huguenots in South Africa|Huguenot refugees]] settled in Stellenbosch,<ref name=Botha-155>{{cite book|last=Botha|first=Colin Graham|title=The French refugees at the Cape|year=1921|publisher=Cape Times Limited|location=Cape Town|page=155|url=https://archive.org/stream/frenchrefugeesat00both#page/154/mode/2up/search/stellenbosch|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> [[grape]]s were planted in the fertile valleys around Stellenbosch and soon it became the centre of the South African [[wine]] industry.<ref name=\"Martin\"/>\n\nIn 1710 a fire destroyed most of the town, including the first church, all the Company property and twelve houses. Only two or three houses were left standing.<ref name=Trotter-174,179>{{cite book|last=Trotter|first=A.F.|title=Old Cape Colony a chronicle of her men and houses from 1652\u20131806|year=1903|publisher=A. Constable & co., ltd.|location=Westminster|pages=174, 179|url=https://archive.org/stream/oldcapecolonychr00trot#page/174/mode/2up/search/fire|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> When the church was rebuilt in 1723 it was located on what was then the outskirts of the town, to prevent any similar incident from destroying it again. This church was enlarged a number of times since 1723 and is currently known as the \"Moederkerk\" (Mother Church).\n\nThe first school had been opened in 1683, but education in the town began in earnest in 1859 with the opening of a seminary for the Dutch Reformed Church. [[Rhenish Girls' High School]], established in 1860, is the oldest school for girls in South Africa.<ref name=\"Eikestad\">{{cite web |title=Rhenish prepare for their 150th birthday |work=Eikestad News |publisher=Eikestadnuus |date=2006-02-17 |url=http://www.news24.com/Regional_Papers/Components/Category_Article_Text_Template/0,,387_1883243~E,00.html |access-date=2007-11-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120082322/http://www.news24.com/Regional_Papers/Components/Category_Article_Text_Template/0,,387_1883243~E,00.html |archive-date=20 January 2008}}</ref> A [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]], known as ''het Stellenbossche Gymnasium'', was established in 1866. In 1874 some higher classes became Victoria College and then in 1918 [[Stellenbosch University|University of Stellenbosch]]. The first men's hostel to be established in Stellenbosch was Wilgenhof, in 1903. In 1905 the first women's hostel to be established in Stellenbosch was Harmonie [http://www0.sun.ac.za/harmonie/?cat=6].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www0.sun.ac.za/harmonie/?cat=6 |title=Huisdinge: Harmonie Dameskoshuis |publisher=Sun.ac.za |access-date=2013-07-29}}</ref> Harmonie and Wilgenhof were part of the Victoria College. In 1909 an old boy of the school, [[Paul Roos (rugby player)|Paul Roos]], captain of the first national rugby team to be called the [[South Africa national rugby union team|Springboks]], was invited to become the sixth rector of the school. He remained rector until 1940. On his retirement the school's name was changed to [[Paul Roos Gymnasium]].\n\nIn the early days of the [[Second Boer War]] (1899\u20131902) Stellenbosch was one of the British military bases, and was used as a \"remount\" camp; and in consequence of officers who had not distinguished themselves at the front being sent back to it, the expression \"to be Stellenbosched\" came into use; so much so, that in similar cases officers were spoken of as \"Stellenbosched\" even if they were sent to some other place.\n\n== Population ==\nAt the time of the [[South African National Census of 2011|2011 census]], the population of the urban area of Stellenbosch was 77,476 people in 23,730 households. 50% of the residents spoke [[Afrikaans]] as their [[home language]], 28% spoke [[isiXhosa]], and 8% spoke [[South African English|English]]. (10% of the residents, principally those in student residences, were not asked their language.) 37% of the population identified themselves as \"[[Bantu peoples in South Africa|Black African]]\", 35% as \"[[Coloured]]\", and 26% as \"[[White South African|White]]\".<ref>Combined population statistics of the Main Places [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167010 Welgevonden], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167011 Cloetesville], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167012 Khayamandi], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167014 La Colline], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167015 Tennantville], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167017 Idasvallei], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167018 Stellenbosch], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167019 Onder Papegaaiberg], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167020 Devon Valley], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167022 Dalsig], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167023 Kleingeluk], [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167024 Paradyskloof] and [https://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/167025 Brandwacht], which constitute the continuous urban area.</ref>\n\nThe [[Stellenbosch Municipality]] extends beyond the town of Stellenbosch itself to include rural areas, villages, and the town of [[Franschhoek]]. At the time of 2011 census the municipal population was 155,728, while by 2016 it was estimated to be 173,197.<ref>{{cite report |date=2018 |title=Community Survey 2016: Provincial profile: Western Cape |url=http://cs2016.statssa.gov.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/WesternCape.pdf |publisher=Statistics South Africa |page=8 |access-date=26 July 2018}}</ref> In 2017, the municipality estimated that the population in 2018 would increase to 176,523<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/assets/departments/treasury/Documents/Socio-economic-profiles/2017/wc024_stellenbosch_2017_socio-economic_profile_sep-lg_-_22_december_2017.pdf Stellenbosch Municipality 2017 \u2013 Western Cape Government]</ref>\n\n==Climate and geography==\n[[File:Stellenbosch WC ZA.jpg|thumb|Stellenbosch's eastern suburbs in the winter months. In the background are the snowcapped Jonkershoek Mountains, with the prominent peak \"The Twins\" (elevation of {{convert|1494|m|ft|abbr=on}}) visible.]]\nStellenbosch is {{convert|53|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of [[Cape Town]] via [[National Routes (South Africa)|National Route]] [[N1 road (South Africa)|N1]]. Stellenbosch is in a hilly region of the [[Cape Winelands]], and is sheltered in a valley at an average elevation of {{convert|136|m|0|abbr=on}}, flanked on the west by [[Papegaaiberg]] ({{lang-af|Parrot Mountain}}), which is actually a hill. To the south is [[Stellenbosch Mountain]]; to the east and southeast are the [[Jonkershoek Mountains|Jonkershoek]], [[Drakenstein]], and [[Simonsberg]] mountains. Die Tweeling Pieke ({{lang-af|The Twin Peaks}}) has an elevation of {{convert|1494|m|ft|abbr=on}}; the highest point is Victoria Peak {{convert|1590|m|ft|abbr=on}}. [[Jonkershoek Nature Reserve]] lies about {{convert|9|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of Stellenbosch, and the [[Helderberg Nature Reserve]] is about {{convert|23|km|mi|abbr=on}} south via [[provincial route (South Africa)|provincial route]] [[R44 road (South Africa)|R44]]. Just south of the Helderberg Nature Reserve is [[Strand, Western Cape|Strand]], a [[seaside resort]] [[Resort town|town]]. The soils of Stellenbosch range from dark [[alluvium]] to [[clay]]. This, combined with the well-drained, hilly terrain and [[Mediterranean climate]], prove excellent for [[viticulture]]. Summers are dry and warm to hot, with some February and March days rising to over {{convert|40|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}. Winters are cool, rainy and sometimes quite windy, with daytime temperatures averaging {{convert|16|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}. Snow is usually seen a couple of times in winter on the surrounding mountains. Spring and autumn are colder seasons, when daytime temperatures hover in the 20s.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = Stellenbosch, Western Cape\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 27.7\n|Feb high C = 27.6\n|Mar high C = 26.5\n|Apr high C = 22.7\n|May high C = 19.4\n|Jun high C = 17.8\n|Jul high C = 16.8\n|Aug high C = 17.3\n|Sep high C = 19.2\n|Oct high C = 21.6\n|Nov high C = 24.5\n|Dec high C = 26.2\n|Jan low C = 14.6\n|Feb low C = 14.5\n|Mar low C = 13.5\n|Apr low C = 10.8\n|May low C = 8.9\n|Jun low C = 7.3\n|Jul low C = 6.5\n|Aug low C = 6.9\n|Sep low C = 8.3\n|Oct low C = 9.9\n|Nov low C = 12\n|Dec low C = 13.6\n|Jan precipitation mm = 17\n|Feb precipitation mm = 28\n|Mar precipitation mm = 29\n|Apr precipitation mm = 76\n|May precipitation mm = 120\n|Jun precipitation mm = 130\n|Jul precipitation mm = 113\n|Aug precipitation mm = 116\n|Sep precipitation mm = 62\n|Oct precipitation mm = 55\n|Nov precipitation mm = 36\n|Dec precipitation mm = 20\n|source = [https://en.climate-data.org/africa/south-africa/western-cape/stellenbosch-6770/ Stellenbosch climate]\n}}\n\n== Sport ==\nStellenbosch is a warm weather training venue for cyclists, track and field squads, and triathletes. The Stellenbosch Sports Academy opened its doors in 2012 and hosts several rugby teams on a permanent basis, such as the \nSpringbok Sevens and Western Province.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n==Viticulture and winemaking==\n[[File:Stellenbosch Vineyard.jpg|thumb|left|Vineyards on the outskirts of Stellenbosch, with Helderberg in the background]]\nThe Stellenbosch, [[Paarl]] and [[Franschhoek]] valleys form the [[Cape Winelands]], the larger of the two main wine growing regions in South Africa. The South African wine industry produces about 1,000,000,000 litres of wine annually. Stellenbosch is the primary location for viticulture and viticulture research. Professor [[Abraham Izak Perold|Perold]] was the first Professor of Viticulture at Stellenbosch University. The [[Stellenbosch Wine Route]] established in 1971 by Frans Malan from Simonsig, Spatz Sperling from Delheim and Neil Joubert from Spier, known as Stellenbosch American Express\u00ae Wine Routes since 2002, is a world-renowned and popular [[tourism|tourist]] destination. This route provides visitors the opportunity to experience a wide range of cultivars and includes farms such as Warwick and JC Le Roux.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stellenbosch American Express\u00ae Wine Routes \u2013 Our Story|url=http://www.wineroute.co.za/story.asp|accessdate=2 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209102721/http://www.wineroute.co.za/story.asp|archivedate=9 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe region has a [[mediterranean climate]] with hot dry summers and cool wet winters. Stellenbosch lies at the foot of the Cape Fold mountain range, which provides soil favourable to [[viticulture]]. Grapes grown in this area are mainly used for wine production, as opposed to [[table grapes]]. The region possesses a wide range of soils in the area, from light, sandy soils to decomposed granite. Stellenbosch [[Cabernet Sauvignon]] is beginning to get a good reputation as a fine wine.<ref>[http://www.the-wine-library.co.uk/P-T/S/Terms/Stellenbosch.html The-Wine-Library] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123121701/http://the-wine-library.co.uk/P-T/S/Terms/Stellenbosch.html |date=23 January 2009 }} Short Description of wine in Stellenbosch</ref>\n\n== Stellenbosch University ==\n{{Main|Stellenbosch University}}\n[[File:Eerste River from De Oewer.JPG|thumb|Eerste River in Stellenbosch after heavy rains]]\n[[File:UniStellenbosch.jpg|thumb|upright|right|View over the \"Red Square\" of Stellenbosch University with the peak, \"The Twins\" beyond]]\n\n[[Stellenbosch University]] is one of South Africa's leading [[University|universities]]. This institution has a rich history dating back to 1863 and has 10 [[faculty (division)|faculties]], including [[Engineering]], [[Commerce]], [[Science]] and [[Arts]]. The Department of Electrical and Electronic Engineering is the only university department in the southern hemisphere which has successfully built a communications satellite [[Sunsat]] which was launched in 2000 and orbited the earth for three years.\n\nThe University currently has about 29,000 students. White students in 2014, namely 18 636, constitute 63.4% of all students enrolled.<ref>\"Core statistics 2014\", Stellenbosch University, 2014, [online] http://www.sun.ac.za/english/statistical-profile-2014-test, Accessed: 04/08/2015</ref> Although the official language of the university is [[Afrikaans]], most post-graduate courses are presented in [[English language|English]]. The university is in the process of introducing more [[English language|English]] centered undergraduate courses following mass protest by the student body. The university council with the concurrence of the senate approved a new language policy on 22 June 2016 for implementation from 1 January 2017. Since the campuses are situated in the Western Cape, the university has committed to introducing multilingualism by using the province\u2019s three official languages, namely [[Afrikaans]], [[English language|English]] and [[isiXhosa]].<ref>http://www.sun.ac.za/english/Documents/Language/Final%20Language%20Policy%20June%202016.pdf</ref>\n\n== List of suburbs ==\n\n{{Unreferenced section|date=July 2018}}\n{{clear left}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*Arbeidslus\n*Brandwacht\n*[[Cloetesville]]\n*[[Dalsig]]\n*De Zalze\n*Dennesig\n*Die Boord, previously ''Rhodes Fruit Farms''\n*Die Rant\n*Idas Valley\n*[[Jamestown, Western Cape|Jamestown]]\n*Karindal\n*Krigeville\n*[[Kayamandi]]\n*[[Kylemore, Western Cape|Kylemore]]\n*Welbedaght\n*La Colline\n*[[Mostertsdrift, Western Cape|Mostertsdrift]]\n*Onderpapegaaiberg, also known as ''Vo\u00ebltjiesdorp''\n*Paradyskloof\n*Plankenberg\n*[[Rozendal]]\n*Simonswyk\n*Techno Park\n*Tennantville\n*Town central\n*[[Uniepark, Western Cape|Uniepark]]\n*Universiteitsoord\n*Welgevonden\n{{div col end}}\n\n[[File:Stellenbosch fan Papagaaiberch grut.jpg|thumb|580px|A panorama of Stellenbosch, as seen from ''Papegaaiberg'']]\n\n== List of schools ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=July 2018}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[A.F. Louw Primary School]]\n*[[Bloemhof High School]]\n*[[Bruckner De Villiers Primary School]]\n*[[Cloetesville High School]]\n*[[Cloetesville Primary School]]\n*[[Devonvallei Primary School]]\n*[[Eikestad Primary School]]\n*[[Idasvallei Primary School]]\n*[[Ikaya Primary School]]\n*[[JJ Rhode Primary School]]\n*[[Kayamandi Secondary School]]\n*[[Koelenhof Primary School]]\n*[[Luckhoff Secondary School]]\n*[[Lynedoch Primary School]]\n*[[Pieter Langeveldt Primary School]]\n*[[Paul Roos Gymnasium]]\n*[[Rhenish Girls' High School]]\n*[[Rhenish Primary School]]\n*[[Rietenbosch Primary School]]\n*[[Stellenbosch High School]]\n*[[Stellenbosch Primary School]]\n*[[Stellenzicht Senior Secondary]]\n*[[St. Idas R.C.Primary School]]\n*[[Weber Gedenk Primary School]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2019}}\n*[[Ferdie Bergh]] \u2013 rugby player\n*[[Kees Bruynzeel]] \u2013 Dutch businessman, timber merchant and yachtsman\n*[[Dirk Coetsee]] \u2013 Chancellor (Hoofdheemraad) of the District of Stellenbosch and Drakenstein in South Africa for most of the 1690s and early 1700s\n*[[Danie Craven]] \u2013 rugby administrator\n*[[Giniel de Villiers]] \u2013 Rally driver\n*[[David Earl (composer)|David Earl]] \u2013 composer and pianist\n*[[Arnu Fourie]] \u2013 Paralympic athlete\n*[[Omar Henry (cricketer)|Omar Henry]] \u2013 cricketer\n*[[Johannes Wolfgang Willy Friedlieb Heuer]] \u2013 entrepreneur\n*[[Daniel Hugo]] \u2013 radio producer, lecturer and poet\n*[[Charl Langeveldt]] \u2013 cricketer{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} \n*[[Lee Langeveldt]] \u2013 football player\n*[[Daniel Fran\u00e7ois Malan|D. F. Malan]] \u2013 Prime Minister of South Africa from 1948 to 1954\n*[[Jannie Marais]] (Johannes Henoch Marais) \u2013 mining magnate, politician and philanthropist who co-founded the multi-billion dollar media conglomerate Naspers and the University of Stellenbosch\n*[[JP Pietersen]] \u2013 rugby player\n*[[Paul Roos (rugby player)|Paul Roos]] \u2013 South African rugby union captain\n*[[Anton Rupert]] \u2013 entrepreneur, businessman, conservationist\n*[[Johann Rupert]] \u2013 businessman{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} \n*[[Dana Snyman]] \u2013 journalist, writer and playwright{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} \n*[[Conrad Stoltz]] \u2013 2-time Olympian, 3 time [[XTERRA Triathlon|Xterra]] world champion{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} \n*[[Roger Telemachus]] \u2013 cricketer\n*[[Sampie Terreblanche]] \u2013 Professor in Economics, co-founder of [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]]\n*[[Rick Turner (philosopher)|Richard Turner]] \u2013 philosopher\n*[[Frederik van Zyl Slabbert]] \u2013 anti-apartheid Member of Parliament and leader of opposition, lecturer in sociology\n*[[Hendrik Verwoerd]] \u2013 Prime Minister of South Africa from 1958 to 1966\n\n==Coats of arms==\nThe municipality currently uses a badge<ref>[http://www.stellenbosch.gov.za Stellenbosch]</ref> consisting of a fleur de lis and a cross issuing from a stylised bunch of grapes. In the past the various local authorities used coats of arms.\n\n* Drostdy \u2013 The drostdy (1685\u20131827) was the local authority for the whole Stellenbosch district, including the town. In 1804, when the [[Cape Colony]] was ruled by the [[Batavian Republic]], the government assigned an armorial seal to the drostdy. It depicted the shield of arms of [[Simon van der Stel]] superimposed on an anchor representing Hope, on a golden background.<ref name=stell1>{{citation |last=Pama |first=C. |year=1965| title=Lions and Virgins}}</ref> In 1814, the British occupation authorities ordered the drostdyen to use the royal coat of arms instead.<ref name=drostdy>''Cape Town Gazette'' No 418 (15 January 1814).</ref> Van der Stel's arms were quartered: 1 two red towers on a golden background; 2 a [[peacock]] on a red background; 3 three silver discs or balls stacked 1 over 2 on a red background; 4 a red tower on a golden background. In the centre was a smaller blue shield displaying six silver crescents (or, possibly, ribs) 2, 2 and 2.\n* Municipality (1) \u2013 The Stellenbosch municipality was formed in 1840, to administer the town, but not the rest of the district. Although it was not the legal successor to the drostdy, it adopted the old drostdy seal of arms. A few changes<ref>[http://www.ngw.nl/heraldrywiki/index.php?title=Stellenbosch changes]</ref> were made to the arms over the years: quarters 2 and 3 were changed from red to blue; the peacock was turned to a profile position; the three silver discs or balls were changed to golden rings; the central shield was changed from blue to black. Whether any of these changes was intentional, or whether they were the result of artistic errors, is unclear.\n* Municipality (2) \u2013 The municipal council had a new coat of arms<ref>[http://www.ngw.nl/heraldrywiki/index.php?title=Stellenbosch new coat of arms]</ref> designed by Michael Dawes in 1951. After some improvements, the [[College of Arms]] granted them on 26 June 1952. They were registered at the [[Bureau of Heraldry]] on 31 August 1979.<ref name=boh>[http://www.national.archsrch.gov.za/sm300cv/smws/sm300dl National Archives of South Africa: Data of the Bureau of Heraldry]</ref> The new design was a golden shield displaying the three towers from the Van der Stel arms, and a red fess displaying the peacock between golden rings. The crest was an anchor entwined with oak leaves and acorns. The motto ''Fortis et superbus'' (\"Strong and proud\") was chosen.\n* Divisional council (1) \u2013 The divisional council, established in 1855, administered the rural areas outside the town. At some point, it adopted the plain Van der Stel arms, i.e. a golden shield displaying three red towers.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n[[File:Arms of the Divisional Council of Stellenbosch, WC, ZA.svg|thumb|83px|right|Stellenbosch Divisional Council coat of arms (1970)]]\n* Divisional council (2) \u2013 The divisional council had its arms re-designed by [[Cornelis Pama]] in 1970, and registered them at the [[Bureau of Heraldry]] on 30 October 1970.<ref name=boh /> The shield was divided down the centre into gold and red, and the three towers were counterchanged. A red tower was added as a crest.\n* ''Kaya Mandi'' \u2013 The local authority for the Black township of Kaya Mandi registered arms at the Bureau on 27 November 1987.<ref name=boh />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tygerberg Zoo]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons|Stellenbosch|Stellenbosch}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Stellenbosch}}\n*[http://www.stellenbosch.gov.za Stellenbosch Municipality]\n*[http://www.stellenbosch.travel/ Stellenbosch Tourism Bureau]\n*[http://www.eikestadnuus.co.za/News/articles Eikestad Nuus]\n\n{{Cape Winelands District Municipality}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Stellenbosch| ]]\n[[Category:Wine regions of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1679]]\n[[Category:Populated places founded by Afrikaners]]\n[[Category:University towns in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Stellenbosch Local Municipality]]\n[[Category:1679 establishments in the Dutch Empire]]\n[[Category:Populated places established by the Dutch East India Company]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the town|the university|Stellenbosch University|the municipality|Stellenbosch Local Municipality}}\n{{Use South African English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Stellenbosch\n| other_name                      = Eikestad\n| image_skyline                   = StellenboschWC-Aerial.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Stellenbosch, South Africa's second-oldest urban area (town), with Great Drakenstein and Stellenbosch Mountains beyond\n| nickname                        = ''Eikestad'' (\"City of Oaks\")\n| pushpin_map                     = South Africa Western Cape#South Africa\n| pushpin_relief = 1\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|33|56|12|S|18|51|41|E|region:ZA|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{RSA}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Provinces 