          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1993|01|11}}\n| birth_place           = [[Ahmedabad]], [[Gujarat]], India\n| height                = 1.63 m (5 ft 5 in)\n| turnedpro             = May 2009\n| plays                 = Right (two-handed backhand)\n| careerprizemoney      = [[US$]]335,265\n| singlesrecord         = {{tennis record|won=268|lost=217}}\n| singlestitles         = 11 [[International Tennis Federation|ITF]]\n| AustralianOpenresult  = Q2 ([[2019 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles Qualifying|2019]])\n| FrenchOpenresult      = Q1 ([[2018 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles Qualifying|2018]], 2019)\n| Wimbledonresult       = Q2 ([[2018 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles Qualifying|2018]], 2019)\n| USOpenresult          = Q2 ([[2019 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles Qualifying|2019]])\n| Othertournaments      = yes\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 160 (2 March 2020) \n| currentsinglesranking = No. 160 (2 March 2020)\n| doublesrecord         = {{tennis record|won=200|lost=166}}\n| doublestitles         = 1 [[WTA 125K Series|WTA 125K]], 17 ITF\n| highestdoublesranking = No. 119 (2 March 2020)\n| currentdoublesranking = No. 119 (2 March 2020)\n| Team                  = yes\n| FedCupresult          = {{tennis record|won=18|lost=14}}\n| updated               = 2 March 2020\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Country|{{IND}}}}\n{{Medal|Sport|Women's tennis}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Asian Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2018 Asian Games|2018 Jakarta]]|[[Tennis at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Women's singles|Women's Singles]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Ankita Ravinderkrishan Raina''' (born 11 January 1993<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100124146|title=Ankita Raina |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref>) is an Indian professional tennis player and the current Indian No. 1 in both women\u2019s singles (since 2013) and doubles (since 2019).\n\nRaina has won one [[WTA 125K series|WTA Challenger]] in doubles, along with eleven singles and seventeen doubles titles on the [[ITF Women's Circuit]]. In April 2018, she entered the top 200 singles rankings for the first time, becoming only the fifth player representing India to achieve this feat.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Srinivasan|first1=Kamesh|title=Ankita Raina in top-200|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/tennis/ankita-in-top-200/article23484503.ece|accessdate=18 April 2018|date=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ankita Raina becomes only third Indian woman tennis player to break into top 200 singles rankings|url=https://www.firstpost.com/sports/ankita-raina-becomes-only-third-indian-woman-tennis-player-to-break-into-top-200-singles-rankings-4425623.html|accessdate=18 April 2018|agency=PTI|date=10 April 2018}}</ref> Raina has also won gold medals in the women's singles and mixed-doubles events at the [[2016 South Asian Games]], and won a bronze medal in singles at the [[Tennis at the 2018 Asian Games|2018 Asian Games]].\n\nPlaying for [[India Fed Cup team|India]] at the [[Fed Cup]], Raina has a win-loss record of 18\u201314.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fedcup.com/en/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100124146|title=Ankita Raina |accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref> She has notable wins over [[Zhu Lin (tennis)|Zhu Lin]] (CHN) and [[Yulia Putintseva]] (KAZ), both at the [[2018 Fed Cup]].\n\n==Personal life==\nRaina was born in the western Indian state of [[Gujarat]] to a [[Kashmiri Pandit]] family. Her family hails from the town of [[Tral]] in [[Pulwama|Pulwama district]], [[Kashmir]]. Raina is fluent in [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], and English. Raina briefly studied at [[Brihan Maharashtra]].\n\nAt the national events, Raina has represented her home state [[Gujarat]]. Her idols growing up were [[Roger Federer]], [[Rafael Nadal]], [[Serena Williams]] and [[Sania Mirza]].\n\nRaina trains at the [[Hemant Bendrey Tennis Academy]] at the [[Deccan Gymkhana#PYC Hindu Gymkhana|PYC Hindu Gymkhana]] in [[Pune]], and is coached by Hemant Bendrey.<ref>[https://celebrityhubspot.com/ankita-raina-biography-profile-records-awards-achievement/ Ankita Raina - Bio]</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:2018 Roland Garros Qualifying Tournament - 55 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|220px|Raina playing in the qualifying competition of the [[2018 French Open]] \u2013 her first Grand Slam tournament.]]\nRaina started playing tennis at the age of five. Following a promising junior career, Raina made her first professional appearance in 2009, at a small ITF tournament in Mumbai. In 2010, she continued to participate in local ITF events with limited success. Raina's 2011 season saw her advance to three ITF circuit finals in doubles, winning one with countrywoman Aishwarya Agrawal. In 2012, she won her first professional singles title in New Delhi and won three more in doubles. This was followed by a few years of mediocre results on the [[ITF Women's Circuit]].\n\nRaina won two matches at the [[2017 Mumbai Open]], advancing to the biggest quarterfinal of her career. This would turn out to be her breakthrough tournament. In April 2018, she reached a ranking of world No. 181 after winning a $25K ITF title, becoming the fifth Indian national to crack to the top-200 ladies singles rankings, following [[Nirupama Sanjeev]], [[Sania Mirza]], [[Shikha Uberoi]], and [[Sunitha Rao]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Srinivasan |first1=Kamesh |title=Ankita Raina in top-200 |url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/tennis/ankita-in-top-200/article23484503.ece |accessdate=10 September 2018 |date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Ankita won the bronze medal in the [[2018 Asian Games|Asian Games]] at Jakarta, Indonesia in singles event. Raina and [[Sania Mirza]] are the only players representing India to have won a singles medal at the Asian Games.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ankita Raina settles for bronze at Asian Games |url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/tennis/ankita-raina-settles-for-bronze-at-asian-games/article24758802.ece |accessdate=23 August 2018 |agency=PTI |date=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 Kunming Open]], Raina got her first top-100 win, defeating [[Samantha Stosur]], former [[U.S. Open (tennis)|US Open]] champion and top 10 player, scoring the biggest win of her career. In October 2019, Raina entered the top 150 doubles rankings for the first time, after reaching the finals of the [[2019 Suzhou Ladies Open]] with partner [[Rosalie van der Hoek]]. She bettered this feat by winning two back-to-back ITF titles in [[Nonthaburi]] alongside [[Bibiane Schoofs]]; followed by reaching her first [[Women's Tennis Association|WTA]] semifinal at the [[2020 Thailand Open]] alongside Rosalie. This gave Raina a new career-high raking of No. 123 in doubles.\n\n==Playing style==\n{{unsourced section|date=January 2020}}\nRaina is a steady baseliner who primarily relies on her speed and counterpunching abilities to outlast her opponents.\nShe hits with plenty of topspin on both her forehand and backhand, and can hit in all directions comfortably. She also uses the backhand slice quite often, as a way of varying the pattern of a rally.\nRaina is comfortable with volleying, and approaches the net whenever she gets her opponent running or out of position. She doesn't use the drop shot or lob too frequently, but brings them out as a surprise tactic.\nRaina's biggest strength is her baseline consistency. She can stay toe-to-toe with most players from the back of the court, and can get a majority of shots back in play.\nRaina has a solid first serve, but it is her second serve that gives her an advantage at the start of a point. She can hit a good kick serve, which opens up the court for an easy putaway.\nRaina also has a good return of serve, and is capable of neutralizing most big serves by sending them back with precision. She is also quite efficient at the net, and can take the attack to the opponent on fast courts with her purposeful volleys.\nRaina's biggest weakness is the lack of firepower on her groundstrokes. She can't match the raw muscle strength of the top players, and so is frequently in danger of getting blown off the court. Recently, she was been moving a lot better on the court as well.\n\n==Sponsorship and equipment==\nIn her junior years, Raina was helped by [[Dishman Pharmaceuticals and Chemicals]] to participate in overseas junior tournaments. Since then, she has been supported by [[Bharat Forge]] and Lakshya. Most recently, Raina has signed sponsorship deals with the Sports Authority of Gujarat and [[Yonex]], and she is officially employed with [[ONGC]].<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Game Changers\n|last=Swamy\n|first=Narain\n|date=2 September 2015\n|access-date=15 March 2016\n|url=http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31806&articlexml=GAME-CHANGERS-02092015025015\n}}</ref> Hence, Raina uses [[Yonex]] racquets and clothing. [[Adani Group]] is her current supporter.\n\nIn 2013, Raina met [[Narendra Modi]], India's then-future prime minister, and officially was recognised under the Shaktidhoot scheme and hence became a part of India's goal of reaching Olympic podiums.\n\n==WTA 125K series finals==\n===Doubles: 1 (1 title)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Result\n!class=\"unsortable\"|W\u2013L\n!{{ns}}Date{{ns}}\n!Tournament\n!Surface\n!Partner\n!Opponents\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| <small>1\u20130</small>\n| [[2018 OEC Taipei WTA Challenger \u2013 Doubles|{{dts|Nov 2018}}]]\n| bgcolor=silver|[[Taipei Open|WTA Taipei]], Taiwan\n| Carpet\n| {{flagicon|IND}} [[Karman Thandi]]\n| {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Olga Doroshina]] <br/> {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Natela Dzalamidze]]\n| 6\u20133, 5\u20137, [12\u201312], ret.\n|}\n\n==ITF circuit finals==\n===Singles: 21 (11 titles, 10 runner\u2013ups)===\n{|\n|-valign=top\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" \n! Legend\n|- style=\"background:#f88379;\"\n| $100,000 tournaments\n|- style=\"background:#f7e98e;\"\n| $75,000/$80,000 tournaments\n|- style=\"background:#addfad;\"\n| $50,000/$60,