la3=_everton1314t\n|pattern_b3=_everton1314t\n|pattern_ra3=_everton1314t\n|pattern_so3=_everton1314t\n|leftarm3=000000\n|body3=000000\n|rightarm3=000000\n|shorts3=000042\n|socks3=FFFFFF\n| prevseason         = [[2012\u201313 Everton F.C. season|2012\u201313]]\n| nextseason         = [[2014\u201315 Everton F.C. season|2014\u201315]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2013\u201314 season''' was [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]'s 22nd season in the [[Premier League]] and 60th consecutive season in the top division of [[Football in England|English football]]. It was also Everton's 115th season of league football and [[List of Everton F.C. seasons|117th season in all competitions]]. It was the first season without [[David Moyes]] as manager since 2002, with Moyes leaving Everton to succeed [[Alex Ferguson]] as manager of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. In addition, the club crest was redesigned ahead of this season for the first time since 2000. On 5 June 2013, [[Roberto Mart\u00ednez]] was announced as the new Everton manager, having left his post at relegated [[FA Cup]] holders [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Roberto Martinez: Everton appoint former Wigan manager|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22750453|accessdate=17 June 2013|date=5 June 2013}}</ref> Everton finished in sixth position in the domestic league in the [[2012\u201313 Everton F.C. season|previous season]], missing out on qualification for the [[UEFA Europa League]], meaning it failed to qualify for any [[UEFA#Competitions|European competitions]] for the fourth season running.\n\nEverton's [[Premier League]] campaign began in August 2013 with Mart\u00ednez changing their style of play to a possession based, attractive brand of football which initially led to three successive draws to start the season.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/everton/10422651/Roberto-Martinez-is-transforming-Everton.html | title=Roberto Mart\u00ednez is transforming Everton | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> A first victory came in the next match 1\u20130 against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and by Christmas Everton had only suffered one defeat, a run which included a win over Moyes' Manchester United, the first time the club had tasted success at [[Old Trafford]] in 21 years. The team almost went an entire year unbeaten at home but lost 1\u20130 against [[Sunderland A.F.C|Sunderland]] on [[Boxing Day]]. Everton's progress stalled somewhat in the early part of 2014 with three losses in four games against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and Chelsea, before winning seven league games in a row for the first time since 1987. The spell contained perhaps Everton's best performance of the season when they defeated [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 3\u20130. The streak was ended with a 3\u20132 home defeat by [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], but Everton returned to do the double over Manchester United for the first time since 1969. Moyes was sacked as their manager a day later. Two defeats in a row after this ended Everton's [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] hopes but a finish of 5th in the league table is their highest in five years with Everton qualifying for next season's [[2014\u201315 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]. Mart\u00ednez utilised the [[Loan (sports)|loan]] market during the season, with [[Romelu Lukaku]] (on loan from Chelsea) being Everton's top scorer with 16 goals in all competitions. The emergence of young players such as [[Ross Barkley]], [[John Stones]] and summer signing [[James McCarthy (footballer)|James McCarthy]] was also a feature of his debut season in charge, with Barkley going on to be selected for [[2014 FIFA World Cup squads#England|England's World Cup squad]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2616692/Roberto-Martinez-not-pressure-sell-young-stars-Ross-Barkley-John-Stones.html | title=Roberto Martinez not under pressure to sell young stars Ross Barkley and John Stones | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}} Right back [[S\u00e9amus Coleman]] was named Everton's player of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/history/coleman-is-player-of-the-season |title=Coleman is Players of the Season |publisher=[[Everton F.C.]] |accessdate=17 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508174802/http://www.evertonfc.com/history/coleman-is-player-of-the-season |archivedate=8 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn the cup competitions Everton lost in the sixth round of the [[2013\u201314 FA Cup|FA Cup]] (entered at round three) and the third round of the [[2013\u201314 Football League Cup|League Cup]] (entered at round two).\n\n==Season overview==\n\n===July===\nEverton announced on 25 May 2013 that the club would be competing in the inaugural edition of the [[International Champions Cup]], based in venues across the United States and in one European city, and held between 27 July and 7 August 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everton Heading Stateside|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2013/05/25/everton-to-head-stateside|publisher=Everton FC|work=evertonfc.com|accessdate=17 June 2013|date=25 May 2013}}</ref> The opening fixtures were announced four days later, with Everton playing [[2012\u201313 Serie A]] champions [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in the first round.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blues To Face Italian Champions|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2013/05/29/blues-to-face-italian-champions|publisher=Everton FC|work=evertonfc.com|accessdate=17 June 2013|date=29 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nBetween 8 and 9 July 2013, [[Roberto Mart\u00ednez]] signed three players who last season played for his former club [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]: \n* [[Arouna Kon\u00e9]], a 29-year-old Ivorian striker who scored 11 goals in his debut Premier League campaign in the previous season. Everton met a \u00a35 million release clause and beat off the competition of [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] to sign him.<ref name=\"Kone\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23230927 | title=Arouna Kone: Everton sign Ivory Coast striker from Wigan Athletic | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Antol\u00edn Alcaraz]], a 30-year-old Paraguayan central defender who joined on a free transfer after his contract at Wigan had expired. He had been at Wigan for three seasons but saw his 2012\u201313 season curtailed due to a groin injury.<ref name=\"transfers\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23247458 | title=Antolin Alcaraz and Joel Robles rejoin Martinez at Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Joel Robles]], a 23-year-old Spanish goalkeeper who had spent last year on loan to Wigan from [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]. He joined on a five-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2013/07/09/blues-sign-joel-robles | title=Blues Sign Joel Robles | publisher=[[Everton F.C.]] | accessdate=13 July 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402165853/http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2013/07/09/blues-sign-joel-robles | archive-date=2 April 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nEverton also signed 19-year-old Spanish forward [[Gerard Deulofeu]] on a season-long loan from [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] the following day, on 10 July 2013.<ref name=\"Delofeu\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23264102 | title=Barcelona loan Gerard Deulofeu to Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===August===\nEverton's [[2013\u201314 Premier League|Premier League]] campaign began on 17 August with a 2\u20132 draw away to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], during which [[Ross Barkley]] scored his first goal for the club.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23644749 | title=Norwich 2\u20132 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref> New manager [[Roberto Mart\u00ednez]] saw his first competitive win come in the second round of the [[2013\u201314 Football League Cup|League Cup]] with Everton needing extra time to defeat League One [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23776650 | title=Everton 2\u20131 Stevenage | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===September===\nOn the final day of the summer transfer window Everton brought three players into the club:\n*[[James McCarthy (footballer)|James McCarthy]], a 22-year-old central midfielder who had previously been at Wigan for four years. Everton paid \u00a313&nbsp;million for the player.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/transfer-news-everton-agree-13m-deal-for-wigan-midfielder-james-mccarthy--and-complete-loan-deal-for-romelu-lukaku-8794357.html | title=Transfer news: Everton agree \u00a313m deal for Wigan midfielder James McCarthy - and complete loan deal for Romelu Lukaku | newspaper=[[The Independent]] | accessdate=3 September 2013 | location=London | first=Simon | last=Rice | date=2 September 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Romelu Lukaku]] on a season-long loan from [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. He had been on loan at [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] last season, scoring 17 goals in 35 league games.<ref name=\"sept transfers\">{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2409320/Everton-sign-Romelu-Lukaku-Gareth-Barry-loan.html | title=Everton complete Lukaku loan swoop despite late interest from West Brom... and Barry joins too | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=3 September 2013 | location=London | first=Graeme | last=Yorke | date=2 September 2013}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}}\n*[[Gareth Barry]], a 32-year-old defensive midfielder also on a season-long loan from [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. He has made 53 appearances for [[England national football team|England]].<ref name=\"sept transfers\"/>\n\nTwo long standing Everton players were sold:\n\n*[[Marouane Fellaini]] left for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in a \u00a327.5 million deal.<ref name=\"MF VA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2013/09/02/blues-confirm-five-deals | title=Blues Confirm Five Deals | publisher=[[Everton F.C.]] | accessdate=3 September 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905103357/http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2013/09/02/blues-confirm-five-deals | archive-date=5 September 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Victor Anichebe]] was transferred to West Bromwich Albion in a deal which could rise to \u00a36&nbsp;million. The striker had made 168 appearances for the club, scoring 26 goals.<ref name=\"MF VA\"/>\n\nEverton's first league win of the season came with a 1\u20130 home success over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] with [[Steven Naismith]] getting the game's only goal.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23999387 | title=Everton 1\u20130 Chelsea | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref> They then came back from 2\u20131 down to beat [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] 3\u20132 at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]] as [[Leighton Baines]] scored two free-kicks and [[Romelu Lukaku]] became the first Everton player since [[Alan Ball, Jr.|Alan Ball]] in 1966 to score a winner on their debut. The result also made [[Roberto Mart\u00ednez]] the first ever manager in the club's history to be unbeaten in their first six games.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/everton-fc-fightback-shows-plenty-6079086 | title=Everton FC fightback shows plenty of positives for the Blues | newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]] | accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> However, the run did not last as in the next fixture [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] won 2\u20131 in the third round of the [[2013\u201314 Football League Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24122195 | title=Fulham 2\u20131 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> New striker Lukaku continued his early form for the club by scoring two goals in the next league game against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in a match where Everton led 3\u20130 at half-time and survived a second half comeback to win 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24201002 | title=Everton 3\u20132 Newcastle | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===October===\nEverton's unbeaten run in the Premier League at the start of the season came to an end on 5 October when it was defeated by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] by 3\u20131 at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24350210 | title=Manchester City 3\u20131 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=5 October 2013| accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref> After the international break the following week, Everton returned to winning ways with a 2\u20131 home victory over [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], which saw [[Steven Pienaar]] score the winning goal just 10 seconds after coming off the bench, making his return to the side from a hamstring injury.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everton 2-1 Hull City|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24504051|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=27 October 2013|date=19 October 2013}}</ref> A 2\u20130 away win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] the following week saw [[Romelu Lukaku]] score his fifth goal in as many league appearances for Everton, and momentarily moved the club into fourth position on the league table.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aston Villa 0-2 Everton|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24591399|work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=27 October 2013|date=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===November===\nEverton began the month with a 0\u20130 home draw against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] which meant the club had only suffered one defeat from their opening 10 games in successive seasons for the first time in its history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crystal Palace v Everton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24783073|work=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref> Another 0\u20130 draw followed before the first [[Merseyside derby]] of the season during which Everton came from 2\u20131 down to lead 3\u20132, before an 89th minute [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] goal saw the game end 3\u20133.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24969016 | title=Everton 3\u20133 Liverpool | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> Everton returned to winning ways by defeating [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] 4\u20130 with both [[Gerard Deulofeu]] and [[Bryan Oviedo]] scoring their first league goals for the club. [[Romelu Lukaku]] continued his impressive start to the season by scoring his eighth goal in ten games as Everton finished the month in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] places.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25063878 | title=Everton 4\u20130 Stoke City | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> With Oviedo and [[S\u00e9amus Coleman]] both scoring it was the first time in Everton's history that both fullbacks found the net during a game.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2516588/Gerard-Deulofeu-showed-hes-destined-greatness-Barcelona-Evertons-win-Stoke.html | title='Sublime' Deulofeu showed why he's destined for greatness with Barcelona in Everton's win over Stoke | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=2 December 2013 | location=London | first=Dominic | last=King | date=1 December 2013}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}}\n\n===December===\nThe next fixture saw [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] manager [[David Moyes]] face his former club for the first time and it was Everton who won 1\u20130 to record their first victory at [[Old Trafford]] for the first time in 21 years with another goal from Oviedo.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25115886 | title=Manchester United 0\u20131 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref> Deulofeu scored an 84th-minute goal to earn a 1\u20131 draw with league leaders [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at the [[Emirates Stadium]] in the next fixture.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25173164 | title=Arsenal 1\u20131 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=9 December 2013}}</ref> Everton then beat [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] at home for the 21st consecutive time with a 4\u20131 win as [[Leon Osman]] scored on his 300th league appearance for the club.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/premier-league-match-facts-everton-v-fulham-171623220--sow.html | title=Premier League - Late show sees Everton drub Fulham to go fourth | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref> Everton then travelled to [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea]] and won 2\u20131, maintaining their record of never having lost to the Welsh side in any fixture.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25387089 | title=Swansea City 1\u20132 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref> The club then suffered a setback to bottom of the table [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], losing at home in the league for the first time in a year, after [[Tim Howard]] conceded an early penalty and was sent off in the 25th minute.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25442273 | title=Everton 0\u20131 Sunderland | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref> Winning ways were restored in the following fixture against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] with goals from Coleman and Lukaku, his first in five league starts, to ensure Everton ended 2013 fourth in the table.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25482673 | title=Everton 2\u20131 Southampton| work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===January===\nThe new year began with Everton travelling to the [[Britannia Stadium]] to face [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] and they earned a 1\u20131 draw courtesy of a stoppage time [[Leighton Baines]] penalty.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25513272 | title=Stoke City 1\u20131 Everton| work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> A comfortable progression into the fourth round of the [[2013\u201314 FA Cup|FA Cup]] followed by beating [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] 4\u20130 with striker [[Nikica Jelavi\u0107]] scoring his first goals of the season.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25531987 | title=Everton 4\u20130 Queens Park Rangers| work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> Everton's first league win of 2014 was a 2\u20130 home success over [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], meaning the side had now earned 42 points from their last 51 at Goodison Park.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25600463 | title=Everton 2\u20130 Norwich City| work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> The club then saw off [[Football League One|League One]] side [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] 4\u20130 to reach the fifth round of the FA Cup,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25789296 | title=Stevenage 0\u20134 Everton| work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> but then suffered their biggest derby defeat since 1982 as [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] thrashed them 4\u20130 at Anfield.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25822244 | title=Liverpool 4-0 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[List of English football transfers winter 2013\u201314|January transfer window]] Everton brought two players into their first team squad:\n* [[Aiden McGeady]], an [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Irish]] international winger from Russian side [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25696809 | title=Transfer window: Everton sign winger Aiden McGeady | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Lacina Traor\u00e9]], a six-foot eight [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivorian]] centre forward on loan for the rest of the season from [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11671/9131878/transfer-news-monaco-striker-lacina-traore-seals-loan-move-to-everton | title=Transfer news: Monaco striker Lacina Traore seals loan move to Everton | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe club also sold two players during the month:\n* [[Nikica Jelavi\u0107]]'s two-year stay at the club ended after he moved to [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]. The striker had enjoyed a fast start for Everton by scoring nine goals in his first thirteen games, but netted just two goals in the whole of 2013. He had fallen behind [[Romelu Lukaku]] as the first choice striker and also moved in a bid to improve his chances of selection in [[Croatia national football team|Croatia's]] squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25691329 | title=Transfer window: Hull plan talks with Nikica Jelavic | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n* [[John Heitinga]] moved to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] after four and a half years at Everton. He had struggled for first team football during the season having failed to start a single league game, but did score on his final appearance for the club in an FA Cup fixture against [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11681/9144641/transfer-news-fulham-sign-evertons-dutch-defender-john-heitinga | title=Transfer news: Fulham sign Everton's Dutch defender John Heitinga | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n[[Kevin Mirallas]] scored a fantastic 25 yard freekick as Everton came from a goal down to beat [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25892891 | title=Everton 2\u20131 Aston Villa | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> Everton lost for the second time in three games as [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] defeated them 1\u20130 at White Hart Lane,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26004450 | title=Tottenham Hotspur 1\u20130 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> but their form in the FA Cup continued with a 3\u20131 home success over [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] to reach the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26105962 | title=Everton 3\u20131 Swansea City | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> The club then lost a second league game in a row for the first time this season when [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] scored a stoppage time winner at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26202633 | title=Chelsea 1\u20130 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n[[Romelu Lukaku]] returned from an ankle injury to score a late goal in a 1\u20130 win over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] to begin March,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26300994 | title=Everton 1\u20130 West Ham | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> but Everton were knocked out of the FA Cup following a 4\u20131 defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] which means the club have now failed to beat the Gunners in the last 20 away meetings.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26395193 | title=Arsenal 4\u20131 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> [[S\u00e9amus Coleman]]'s miscued shot in the last minute of the next game against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] ensured Everton responded with a 2\u20131 victory to be placed sixth in the table.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26493214 | title=Everton 2\u20131 Cardiff | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> The club then won four league games in a row for the first time in six years by defeating [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] 3\u20130 thanks to an amazing solo goal from [[Ross Barkley]] who dribbled from inside his own half to score the opener. It was Everton's biggest win at Newcastle in 47 years.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/premier-league-matchpack-newcastle-united-v-everton-195308823--sow.html | title=Premier League - Barkley solo effort inspires Everton victory | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref> Everton ended the month with a fifth successive victory for the first time since 2002 with a 3\u20131 away win over [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://espnfc.com/blog/_/name/everton/id/2237?cc=5739 | title=Substitutes keep Everton marching on | publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] | accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===April and May===\nEverton beat Champions League rivals [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 3\u20130 at home in a performance manager Mart\u00ednez described as tactically perfect. The result left the side a point behind the fourth placed Gunners with a game in hand.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26807037 | title=Everton 3\u20130 Arsenal | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> A seventh successive league win for the first time since 1987 followed with a 1\u20130 victory over [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] which moved the club into fourth place. It also took them to 65 points, the highest total Everton have ever amassed in a Premier League season.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26898605 | title=Sunderland 0\u20131 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref> The club then handed the initiative back to Arsenal in the race for Champions League football as they lost 3\u20132 at home to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26716889 | title=Everton 2\u20133 Crystal Palace | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> Everton responded with a 2\u20130 victory over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and in doing so did the double over for the reigning champions for the first time since 1969.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27007492 | title=Everton 2\u20130 Manchester United | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> Everton's previous manager [[David Moyes]] was sacked by United a day later after just 10 months in charge.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27107795 | title=David Moyes: Manchester United manager sacked by club | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref> However, Everton then lost 2\u20130 against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] (with own goals from [[Antol\u00edn Alcaraz]] and [[S\u00e9amus Coleman]]) and 3\u20132 to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] to end their cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27273312 | title=Hull City 2\u20132 Everton | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref>tyfgjmhik\n\n==Pre-season==\n\n===Friendlies===\n{{Football box collapsible\n| date       = {{Nowrap|14 July}}\n| round      = \n| time       = 17:00 [[Central Euro